body: The team also noticed the memory issue recently both from internal and external channels.  I am looking at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5176. May combine your case along the way.
The result that is returned from Run() call are IDisposables that hold pointers to the natively allocated memory. If you do not dispose them, they will continue to accumulate allocated memory.
@fco-jle: please confirm if the result disposal solve your problem.

Thank you for your answers. 

We tried the suggested solution, doing something along the lines:

`var result = session.Run(inputNames, inputValues);
{Do something with result};
 result.Dispose();`

But it did not solve the issue, the memory keeps increasing. 

Our team have noticed that the memory increase has to do with the use of Zipmaps, and it seems that, when the model is being converted and saved in python, setting the zipmap option to False has improved performance and solve the memory issue in C#.

So we believe that the memory leak is related to the use of Zipmap. It might be worth mentioning that the regression models that we are using do not cause the memory leak, even with the use of zipmaps, so it might be related only to the classification output.  

We are still testing.

issue.title: Add additional test cases to check for leaks in thread pool creation / destruction

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Add additional test cases such as ThreadPoolTest.TestPoolCreation_10Iter to create and destroy thread pools to watch for any memory leaks.  Running under Valgrind, these tests should show all of the data allocated being deallocated again.  

**Motivation and Context**
Two recent issues https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5176 and https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5292 indicated memory leaks.  The test cases help identify whether or not any of the data structures used in the thread pool are being leaked.  Currently, on WSL, the only data not being de-allocated in these tests are a small number of nsync waiter objects.  This behavior is as expected (the waiter objects should be held on a free list in the nsync library).

Hey @vade, first time I'm hearing of this. I'd never heard of Zipmap until now, and it certainly looks like this is not a part of the conversion process, don't see anything about it in the [PyTorch docs](https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/onnx.html#operator-export-type) either

@fco-jle what framework did you export the model from? If PyTorch, is there a specific `opset_version` that you used to alleviate the issue, or any other export param? Would appreciate any input, thanks!

Seems my memory issue was a subtle issue on my end - using multiple threads along with generators seems to act poorly or I'm misunderstanding a subtlety of python (not a python dev). running serial inference shows acceptable, expected memory usage.

@fco-jle 
In dealing with https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5176, I tested C# API, it turns out in order to make mem flat, one has to dispose inferred results timely and call GC.collect() to ensure releasing, for you case would you mind to further try with dispose and GC.collec() combined after each run?
Some more information - along the way I also tested C/C++ API trying to spot native code leaks by utilizing the built-in mem debugger in ORT:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/platform/windows/debug_alloc.h
while by far no suspicious leaks have ever been spotted.

@fco-jle: Would u mind either confirm the dispose + GC.collect() approch or somehow share maybe a sample model for further investigation? Like stated in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5176, there is unlikely any native leaks from ORT.
